Step 1: Prerequisites
Before getting started, ensure that you have the following prerequisites on your Linux device:

1. Terminal access with sudo privileges
2. An active domain (example: leo.kritica.xyz)
3. Nginx installed (any other web server will also work if you're comfortable with their configuration)
4. A text editor (e.g., nano, vim, or any other text editor of your choice)
5. A Cloudflare account

Step 2: Setup DNS in Cloudflare

1. Log in to your Cloudflare account.
2. Click on `Add a Site` and enter your domain "kritica.xyz".
3. Follow the instructions to set up Cloudflare for your domain by updating the nameservers.
4. Once the DNS is propagated, go to the `DNS` tab.
5. Add an `A` record to point "leo" to the public IP address of your Linux device.

Step 3: Install Basic HTML & CSS for a Coming Soon Page

1. Create a new directory for your web page:

```bash
sudo mkdir -p /var/www/html/leo
```

2. Create an "index.html" file:

```bash
sudo nano /var/www/html/leo/index.html
```

3. Paste the following HTML code into the "index.html" file:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
    <title>Coming Soon</title>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>Coming Soon</h1>
        <p>Our website is under construction. Please check back soon!</p>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```

4. Save and close the file.

5. Create a "style.css" file:

```bash
sudo nano /var/www/html/leo/style.css
```

6. Paste the following CSS code into the "style.css" file:

```css
* {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    box-sizing: border-box;
}

body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    background-color: #f5f5f5;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    height: 100vh;
}

.container {
    background-color: #ffffff;
    border-radius: 12px;
    box-shadow: 0px 4px 6px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
    padding: 40px;
    text-align: center;
}

h1 {
    font-size: 32px;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
}

p {
    font-size: 18px;
    line-height: 1.4;
}
```

7. Save and close the file.

Step 4: Create Nginx Configuration for your Domain

1. Create a new Nginx configuration file:

```bash
sudo nano /etc/nginx/sites-available/leo
```

2. Paste the below Nginx configuration into the file, changing the "server_name" to your domain:

```nginx
server {
   listen 80;
   server_name leo.kritica.xyz;

   root /var/www/html/leo;
   index index.html;

   location / {
       try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
   }
}
```

3. Save and close the file.

4. Create a symbolic link for the configuration file:

```bash
sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/leo /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/
```

5. Test the Nginx configuration:

```bash
sudo nginx -t
```

6. Restart Nginx to apply the changes:

```bash
sudo systemctl restart nginx
```

Step 5: Enable HTTPS with SSL/TLS

1. Install Certbot and the Nginx plugin:

```bash
sudo apt install certbot python3-certbot-nginx
```

2. Run Certbot to obtain and install a certificate:

```bash
sudo certbot --nginx
```

- Select the "leo.kritica.xyz" domain when prompted.
- Choose whether or not to redirect all traffic to HTTPS. We recommend choosing option 2 to redirect.

Step 6: Update Cloudflare SSL/TLS settings

1. Log in to your Cloudflare account and go to the "SSL/TLS" tab.
2. Under "Encryption mode", select "Full (strict)".

That's it! Now you should have a self-hosted coming soon page on your Linux device with a modern, slick design, using the "leo.kritica.xyz" domain and Cloudflare for performance, protection, and general DNS.

