    <div id="bookmarklet-container">
        <div class="bookmarklet-section">
            <label>Name: <input type="text" class="name"></label><br>
            <label>Code: <input type="text" class="code"></label><br>
            <label>Description: <input type="text" class="description"></label><br><br>
            <button class="delete-section">Delete Section</button>
        </div>
    </div>

    <br>
    <button id="add-section">Add Section</button>
    <button id="generate-page">Generate Page</button>
    <br><br>
    <a id="output-link" href="" target="_blank"></a>

    <script>
        const addSectionButton = document.getElementById('add-section');
        const deleteSectionButtons = document.querySelectorAll('.delete-section');
        const generatePageButton = document.getElementById('generate-page');
        const outputLink = document.getElementById('output-link');
        const bookmarkletContainer = document.getElementById('bookmarklet-container');

        addSectionButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
            const newSection = document.createElement('div');
            newSection.innerHTML = `
                <div class="bookmarklet-section">
                    <label>Name: <input type="text" class="name"></label><br>
                    <label>Code: <input type="text" class="code"></label><br>
                    <label>Description: <input type="text" class="description"></label><br><br>
                    <button class="delete-section">Delete Section</button>
                </div>
            `;
            bookmarkletContainer.appendChild(newSection);

            const deleteBtn = newSection.querySelector('.delete-section');
            deleteBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
                deleteBtn.parentElement.remove();
            });
        });

        generatePageButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
            const sections = bookmarkletContainer.children;
            let linksHTML = '';

            for (let i = 0; i < sections.length; i++) {
                const name = sections[i].querySelector('.name').value;
                const code = encodeURIComponent(sections[i].querySelector('.code').value);
                const description = sections[i].querySelector('.description').value;
                linksHTML += `<a href="javascript:${code}">${name}</a> (${description})<br>`;
            }

            const pageTitle = '<h1>Bookmarklets</h1>';
            const generatedPage = `data:text/html;charset=utf-8, ${pageTitle}${linksHTML}`;

            outputLink.setAttribute('href', generatedPage);
            outputLink.innerText = "Click here for the generated page";
        });

        bookmarkletContainer.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
            if (event.target.matches('.delete-section')) {
                event.target.parentElement.remove();
            }
        });
    </script>

</body>
</html>
```

This page creates a section for entering the bookmarklet name, code, and description with the ability to add more sections and generate an output HTML page with the bookmarklets as links. The generated page can be accessed by clicking on the "Click here for the generated page" link. The sections can also be deleted individually by clicking the "Delete Section" button.

In this task, we'll create a Hadoop Java program to perform sentiment analysis by using MapReduce in the Cloudera Hadoop environment. For simplicity, let's assume that we have a small dataset containing positive and negative words.

Step 1: Create the Java program
We'll create a Java program that contains a Mapper, a Reducer, and a Driver class using the Hadoop MapReduce libraries. Save the following code to a file called `SentimentAnalysis.java`:

```java
import java.io.IOException;
import java.util.StringTokenizer;

import org.apache.hadoop.conf.Configuration;
import org.apache.hadoop.fs.Path;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.IntWritable;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.LongWritable;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.Text;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Job;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Mapper;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Reducer;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.lib.input.FileInputFormat;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.lib.output.FileOutputFormat;

public class SentimentAnalysis {

    public static class SentimentMapper extends Mapper<LongWritable, Text, Text, IntWritable> {

        private final static IntWritable one = new IntWritable(1);
        private Text word = new Text();

        public void map(LongWritable key, Text value, Context context) throws IOException, InterruptedException {
            String line = value.toString();
            StringTokenizer tokenizer = new StringTokenizer(line);

            while (tokenizer.hasMoreTokens()) {
                word.set(tokenizer.nextToken().toLowerCase());
                context.write(word, one);
            }
        }
    }

    public static class SentimentReducer extends Reducer<Text, IntWritable, Text, IntWritable> {

        public void reduce(Text key, Iterable<IntWritable> values, Context context)
                throws IOException, InterruptedException {
            int sum = 0;
            for (IntWritable val : values) {
                sum += val.get();
            }
            context.write(key, new IntWritable(sum));
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        Configuration conf = new Configuration();
        Job job = Job.getInstance(conf, "sentiment analysis");

        job.setJarByClass(SentimentAnalysis.class);
        job.setMapperClass(SentimentMapper.class);
        job.setReducerClass(SentimentReducer.class);

        job.setOutputKeyClass(Text.class);
        job.setOutputValueClass(IntWritable.class);

        FileInputFormat.addInputPath(job, new Path(args[0]));
        FileOutputFormat.setOutputPath(job, new Path(args[1]));

        System.exit(job.waitForCompletion(true) ? 0 : 1);
    }
}
```

Step 2: Compile the Java program

To compile the Java program, you need to add the Hadoop JAR to the classpath. For Cloudera, the Hadoop JAR file can be found in `/usr/lib/hadoop`.

```bash
$ javac -cp /usr/lib/hadoop/* SentimentAnalysis.java
$ jar cf sentiment-analysis.jar *.class
```

Step 3: Run the Java program on Cloudera Hadoop

Assuming that you have a file called `input.txt` in the HDFS and a folder called `output` for storing the results, execute the following command to run the MapReduce job:

```bash
$ hadoop jar sentiment-analysis.jar SentimentAnalysis /user/cloudera/input/input.txt /user/cloudera/output
```

After the job is completed, you can see the output in the HDFS output directory:

```bash
$ hadoop fs -cat /user/cloudera/output/*
```

The terminal commands you will use are:

1. Compile the Java program: `javac -cp /usr/lib/hadoop/* SentimentAnalysis.java`
2. Create the JAR file: `jar cf sentiment-analysis.jar *.class`
3. Run the MapReduce job on Cloudera Hadoop: `hadoop jar sentiment-analysis.jar SentimentAnalysis /user/cloudera/input/input.txt /user/cloudera/output`
4. Check the output: `hadoop fs -cat /user/cloudera/output/*`

For this program, you'll need the `hadoop-core` and `hadoop-client` JAR files that are included in Cloudera's distribution.

