To create a simple pivot point indicator in MT4 using MQL4, follow these steps:

1. Open MetaTrader 4 platform.
2. Click on "Tools" in the top menu, then click on "MetaQuotes Language Editor" or press F4.
3. In the MetaEditor window, click on "File" in the top left corner, then click on "New" and choose "Custom Indicator".
4. Name your indicator, for example, "PivotPoint", and click "Next".
5. In the next window, make sure "OnCalculate" event is selected and click "Finish" to generate the basic code structure.
6. Replace the entire code with the following:

```mql4
//+------------------------------------------------------------------+
//|                                                      PivotPoint.mq4|
//|                        Copyright 2021, MetaQuotes Software Corp.|
//|                                             https://www.mql5.com|
//+------------------------------------------------------------------+
#property copyright "Copyright 2021, MetaQuotes Software Corp."
#property link      "https://www.mql5.com"
#property version   "1.00"
#property indicator_chart_window
#property indicator_buffers 1
#property indicator_color1 MediumBlue

double Pivot[];

//+------------------------------------------------------------------+
//| Custom indicator initialization function                         |
//+------------------------------------------------------------------+
int OnInit()
  {
   SetIndexStyle(0,DRAW_LINE);
   SetIndexBuffer(0,Pivot);
   SetIndexLabel(0,"Pivot");
   IndicatorShortName("Pivot Point");

   return(INIT_SUCCEEDED);
  }

//+------------------------------------------------------------------+
//| Custom indicator iteration function                              |
//+------------------------------------------------------------------+
int OnCalculate(const int rates_total,
                const int prev_calculated,
                const datetime &time[],
                const double &open[],
                const double &high[],
                const double &low[],
                const double &close[],
                const long &tick_volume[],
                const long &volume[],
                const int &spread[])
  {
   int i, limit;

   if(prev_calculated == 0)
      limit = rates_total - 1;
   else
      limit = rates_total - prev_calculated;

   for(i = limit; i >= 0; i--)
     {
      double h = high[i];
      double l = low[i];
      double c = close[i];
      Pivot[i] = (h + l + c) / 3.0;
     }

   return(rates_total);
  }

//+------------------------------------------------------------------+
```

7. Click on "File" in the top menu, then click on "Save" or press CTRL+S to save the indicator.
8. Click on "Compile" button in the toolbar or press F7 to compile the indicator.
9. If there are no errors during the compilation process, close the MetaEditor.
10. In the MetaTrader 4 platform, open the "Navigator" window by pressing CTRL+N.
11. Scroll down to "Custom Indicators" in the Navigator window, and your new indicator "PivotPoint" should be listed.
12. Drag and drop the indicator on the EUR/USD chart to see the pivot points.

Please keep in mind that this is just a simple pivot point indicator, and there are many other ways to calculate pivot points and additional support and resistance levels. You can modify the code as needed to match your desired calculations and appearance.

In order to create and host a modern and slick "Browse" page for your online digital book sales platform called Kritica for free in the cloud, you can follow the below steps. This guide will walk you through setting up Firebase for backend services, Cloudflare for DNS and performance optimization, and using Material-UI and React to create a modern user interface.

1. Create a Firebase account and set up a new project:

Go to the Firebase website (https://firebase.google.com/) and sign up for a free account. After signing up, create a new project. Name it "Kritica" and follow the prompts to set it up.

2. Configure Firestore database:

In your Firebase project, click on "Firestore Database" in the left sidebar. Click on "Create database" and select "Start in test mode". This will allow you to add, edit, and delete data in the database without any authentication or security rules.

3. Add books to Firestore:

To add books to your database, click on "Start collection" and name it "books". Add the following fields: "title", "author", "genre", "price", and "coverImageUrl". 

Repeat this process to add several book entries, using real or dummy data.

4. Configure Cloudflare for your domain:

Log into your Cloudflare account, go to the "DNS" tab, and configure your domain kritica.xyz to point to the IP address provided by Firebase Hosting (which will be configured in a later step).

5. Install the required tools:

Install Node.js (https://nodejs.org/en/download/) on your computer. After installing Node.js open your device's command-line interface (CLI) and run the following commands:

```
npm install -g create-react-app
npm install -g firebase-tools
```

6. Create a new React project:

On your CLI, navigate to the folder where you want to create your React project and run:

```
create-react-app kritica
cd kritica
```

7. Install Material-UI:

To create a modern and slick interface, we'll use Material-UI. To install Material-UI, run the following command:

```
npm install @mui/material @emotion/react @emotion/styled
```

8. Install Firebase:

To connect your project to Firebase, run the following command:

```
npm install firebase
```

9. Connect your project to your Firebase project:

Create a file named `firebase.js` in the `src` folder of your React project and add the following code:

```javascript
import firebase from "firebase/app";
import "firebase/firestore";

const firebaseConfig = {
  apiKey: "YOUR_API_KEY",
  authDomain: "YOUR_AUTH_DOMAIN",
  projectId: "YOUR_PROJECT_ID",
  storageBucket: "YOUR_STORAGE_BUCKET",
  messagingSenderId: "YOUR_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID",
  appId: "YOUR_APP_ID",
};

firebase.initializeApp(firebaseConfig);

const firestore = firebase.firestore();

export { firestore };
```

Replace the placeholders with the actual information from your Firebase project. You can find this information in your Firebase project settings under the "General" tab.

10. Create the 'Browse' page in your React project:

Create a folder named `pages` in the `src` folder and create a file named `Browse.js` inside it. Add the following code to create the browse page:

```javascript
import React, { useState, useEffect } from "react";
import { firestore } from "../firebase";
import { Box, Grid, Typography, Card, CardContent, CardMedia } from "@mui/material";

const Browse = () => {
  const [books, setBooks] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchData = async () => {
      const bookRef = firestore.collection("books");
      const snapshot = await bookRef.get();
      const booksData = snapshot.docs.map((doc) => ({ ...doc.data(), id: doc.id }));
      setBooks(booksData);
    };

    fetchData();
  }, []);

  return (
    <Box>
      <Typography variant="h4" marginBottom="1rem">
        Browse Books
      </Typography>
      <Grid container spacing={4}>
        {books.map((book) => (
          <Grid item key={book.id} xs={12} sm={6} md={4}>
            <Card>
              <CardMedia
                component="img"
                height="250"
                image={book.coverImageUrl}
                alt={book.title}
              />
              <CardContent>
                <Typography gutterBottom variant="h5">
                  {book.title}
                </Typography>
                <Typography>{book.author}</Typography>
                <Typography>{book.genre}</Typography>
                <Typography>${book.price}</Typography>
              </CardContent>
            </Card>
          </Grid>
        ))}
      </Grid>
    </Box>
  );
};

export default Browse;
```

11. Add routing and rendering the browse page:

Install React Router:

```
npm install react-router-dom
```

Replace the content inside `src/App.js` with the following code:

```javascript
import React from "react";
import { BrowserRouter as Router, Route, Switch } from "react-router-dom";
import { Container } from "@mui/material";
import Browse from "./pages/Browse";

function App() {
  return (
    <Router>
      <Container maxWidth="lg">
        <Switch>
          <Route path="/" exact component={Browse} />
        </Switch>
      </Container>
    </Router>
  );
}

export default App;
```

12. Deploy your project to Firebase Hosting:

First, log in to Firebase through the command line:

```
firebase login
```

Next, initialize your project:

```
firebase init
```

Choose "Hosting" from the list of options and configure it using your project. Your `public` folder should be set as `build`.

Now, build your React project:

```
npm run build
```

Finally, deploy your project:

```
firebase deploy
```

After the deployment is complete, your 'Browse' page for your Kritica platform is ready and accessible through your domain kritica.xyz. You can now share your project and allow users to browse the available digital books.

